{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_hines_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280659678/1927031301/0171.xml":{"full_text":"30\nANGLICAN CHANGES\nNOTTOAFFECTU.S.\n'fpiscopal Church Has Own\nCommission at Work on\nPrayer Book.\n\u25a0i\nThe various changes and revisions\niti the prayer book of the Church of\nEngland* some of which have caused\nWidespread discussion, notably the\n\u2022Vfction of St. Valentine and St. Nirh\nolas from the church calendar, and\nthe addition of St. Patrick and St.\nFrancis, do not affect the Episcopal\nchurch in the United States, although\nthey will be studied* closely here,\nRight Rev. P. M. Rhinelander of the\nWashington Cathedral said yesterday.\nThe reported changes, Dr. Rhine\nlander said, tend rather to bring the\nmother church closer t 6 the American\nchurch, because t>f the interesting his\ntorical circumstances under which the\nlatter was established. The American\nchurch, however, has its own commis\nsion at work on a revision of the,\nKayer book and the report of this\ndy is expected to be made at Wash\nington in 1928.\nBlack Letter Days.\nAmong the more colorful features\nof the English revision was the altera\ntion of the list of black letter days,\nwithdrawing recognition from certain\nsaints and according it to others.\nBut the American church. Dr.\nRhinelander said, never has had any\nblack letter days and one of the re\nsults of the work of the present* com\nmission probably will be to draw up\nsuch a list, which may include some\nAmerican names of persons promi\nnent in the history of the church. The\nEnglish church, he explained, has red\nletter days and black letter days. The\nfirst are the established Christian fes\ntivals commemorating events in the\nlife of Jesus and the feast days of the\nApostles. These are observed with\nspecial, designated services.\nNear Scotch Form.\nThe black letter days, on the dlher\nhand, are to commemorate various\nhistorical personages notably the\nsaints. At the time of the Reforma\ntion, the English church took over\nmany of these from the Catholic\nchurch, but there is no special observ\nance of the days. The names merely\nare printed in the church calendar.\nThe American church adopted the\nred letter days, but discarded the\nblack letter days althogether. At the\ntime of the adoption of the American\nchurch calendar and prayer book in\n1789, the intention was to remain as\nclose as possible to the English model,\nmaking only such changes as were es\nsential to the national needs\u2014such as\nsubstituting for the prayer for the\nking a prayer for the president. Ac\ntually, however, the American cal\nendar and prayer book are closer to\nthe Scotch Episcopal form than to\nthe English. It is notable, Bishop\nRhinelander said, that the latest re\nvision also departs from the English\ntoward the Scotch precedent.\n20 Saints Evicted.\nTwenty saints in all have been\n\u2022victed from the English calendar\u2014\nmost of them of questionable historical\norigin. The two most notable are St.\nValentine and St. Nicholas.\nSt. Valentine la believed to have\nbeen a martyred Roman priest, al\nthough in the old calendar he was\ncalled a bishop. How hie day became\na lovers' festival never has been\nexplained. Some church writers be\nlieve it is a relic of a pagan custom.\nSt. Nicholas, the popular Santa\nClaus and the patron saint of the\nRussian church, also goes from the\nnew calendar.\nOther black letter days dropped are:\nJanuary\u2014St. Lucian, St. Prlsca.\nFebruary\u2014St. Blasius, St- Agatha.\nROYAL\n\ntkkui about out-\nHOOVER\nj\nYou can now get a Hoover \u2014a\nHoover with the revolutionary\n\u201cPositive Agitation\u201d\u2014in a popular\npriced model \u2014a model marked at\nso modest a figure that, paying for\nit in small monthly amounts, you\nwill never feel its cost.\nYou\u2019ll want this great value in a genu\nine \u201cPositive Agitation\u201d Hoover\u2014at\nonce. So call us up and have one\nof our salesmen bring it out for a\ndemonstration on your own rugs.\nOr, drop in tomorrow and we\u2019ll\ngive you particulars.\nLiberal Allowance\nOn Your Old Cleaner\n\nJR PALAIS ROYAL\u2014Main and Fourth Flocro.\nClogged Calendar\nGives M. C. a Chance\nFor Joke on House\nNumerous requests for \u201cunani\nmous consent to speak\" are made\nin every session of Congress, but it\nremained for Representative How\nard, Democrat, Nebraska, to estab\nlish a precedent by reversing the\nrequest.\nHaving obtained unanimous con\nsent to speak for 20 minutes on a\ncertain day upon a subject not un\nder consideration, he found when\nthe time arrived that the calendar\nwas clogged. He rose and re\nquested \"unanimous consent to be\nallowed not to speak.\"\nLaughter greeted his request, but\nthe speaker heard no objection and\nit was granted.\nMarch-f-Edward, King of the West\nSaxons.\nMay\u2014lnvention of the Cross.\nJune \u2014St. Nicomede, Translation of\nEdward.\nJuly\u2014Translation of St. Martin,\nr^'ptemher\u2014-St. Evurttus, St. Lam\nbert.\nOctober\u2014St. Denys, St. Crispin.\nNovember\u2014Pt. Rtitius, St. Machu\ntus, St. Catherine.\nDecember\u2014St. Lucy, St. Sylvester.\nThe following black letter days are\nadded:,\nJanuary 17, Antony of Egypt: Janu\nary 19, VVulstan, Bishop of Worces\nter; January 26. Polycarp, Bishop of\nSmyrna and martyr; January 27,\nJohn Chrysostom, Bishop of Constan\ntinople and doctor: February 3, Ans\nkar of Sweden, Bishop; March 17, Pat\nrick of Ireland, Bishop: March 20,\nCuthbert, Bishop of Lindisfarne:\nApril 11, Leo 'the Great, Bishop of\nRome:; April 21, Anselm, Archbishop\nof Canterbury; April 30, Catharine of\nSiena, virgin; May 2, Athanasius.\nBishop of Alexandria; May 4, Mon\nnica, matron; May 25, Andhelm,\nBishop of Sherbourne; June 9, Co\nlumba, abbot of Iona; June 14, Basil,\nBishop of Caesarea and Cappadocia;\nJune 22. Alban, martyr (changed from\nJune 17); June 28, Irenaeus, Bishop\nof Lyons; August 6, Oswald, King of\nNorthumbria and martyr; August 20,\nBernard of Clairvaux; September 13,\nCyprian, Bishop of Carthage and\nmartyr (changed from September 26);\nSeptember 16, Ninian, Bishop in Gal\nloway: September 19. Theodore of\nTarsus, Archbishop of Canterbury:\nOctober 4, Francis of Assisi; October\n26. Alfred, King of the West Saxons;\nNovember. 2, commemoration of All\nSouls; November 8, saints, martyrs\nand doctors of the Church of England;\nNovember 16, Hugh, Bishop of 1 Lin\ncoln (changed from November 172;\nNovember 17, Hilda, abbess of Whit\nby; December 4, Clement of Alexan\ndria: December 17, Ignatius, Bishop\nof Antioch and martyr.\nFor the first time St. Patrick and\nSt. Francis are to be included in the\ncalendar of the English church.\nEngineering Courses Assigned.\nFive young engineer officers at Fort\nHumphreys. Va., have been ordered\nto take the engineering course at\nCornell University, Ithaca, N. Y., be\nginning in June next. They are Sec\nond Lieuts. George E. Textor, Clin\nton F. Robinson, Leonard L. Bing\nham, Raymond B. Oxrieder and Wil\nliam C. leaker, jr.\nFor driving a motor hearse so reck\nlessly that he ran into a flock of sheep\nand killed four animals, a man was\nfined in court at Cupar, Scotland, re\ncently.\nHanan Shoes\nExclusively at\nThe Hecht Co.\nTHE SUNDAY STAR, WASHINGTON, D. 0., MARCH 13, 1927-PART 1.\nBUSINESS OUTLOOK\nDEEMED HEALTHY\nEconomists Fail to Sense\nDanger Through Recent\nGovernment Survey.\nBY HARDEN COLFAX.\nResults of a special survey of the\nbusiness and industrial situation\nthroughout the country, which was\ncompleted last week by Government\nagencies that keep their fingers con\nstantly on the pulse of trade life,\nshow nothing to justify outpourings\nby prophets of evil.\nBusiness, generally speaking, is de\ncidedly good. Recessions here and\nthere, which are indicated by certain\nof the trades statistics, are explained\nby especial conditions which have no\npermanent influence upon the general\nsituation.\nEven though there are declines in\ntrade in some lines, such for Instance\nas a decrease of 3 per cent in the\nsales of mail order houses reporting\nto the Federal Reserve Board last\nmonth as compared with February,\n1926, it is pointed out by economists\nthat when comparisons are made\nwith last year, present figures must\nbe set against those resulting from\nextraordinary activity. In other\nwords, there is room for a decrease\nas compared with 1926 conditions\nwhich still would leave 1927 a year\nof, brisk activity and generally good\nbusiness.\nMay Be Belter.\nThe fact is that 1927 may prove\nto be even a better business .year\nthan 1926, all elements considered,\nand nothing has occurred thus far to\ndisprove the faith of those business\nmen and industrialists who are driv\ning ahead to this end.\nJobs appear to be as plentiful as\nlast year, with some shifts necessary\nin employment due to emphasis being\ntransferred from one line of industry\nto another.\nConsumers are likely to receive\ntheir merchandise and their food at\naverage prices lower than the aver\nage throughout 1926. The price level\nlately has stiffened in some lines Luf\nin general has continued to decrease\nthrough the early weeks of 1927.\nOne very significant note was sound\ned in the replies to the special survey\nof business conditions which in it\nself, is sufficient indication of the\nfeeling of confidence in the future en\ntertained by men who have their capl\ntal invested in industry. That Is the\nexpansion of industrial plants. Addi\ntions and new factories are being con\nstructed at a rate higher than any\nperiod since 1920. Those who have ex\npressed fear that American industry\nhas been overbuilt may do well to lis\n1 I\n\u201dA New Palais Royal in the Making\u201d\n%PAL/JS ROYAL\nG Street at Eleventh Telephone Main 8780 Kresge Department Stores, Inc.\nAnnual Sale of Roses, Shrubs and Evergreens!\nBegins at 8 O'Clock\u2014Monday on the Fourth Floor. Use 11th Street Entrance!\nr \u20147-7 1\nEvergreens JSSjSiw- Flower Bulbs\n\u201cE,,,,\n1 T~! Perpetual Hybr